### News
- Elon Musk Building Worlds Most Advanced Spy Satellite Swarm Network for US Gov [Reuters](https://www.reuters.com/technology/space/musks-spacex-is-building-spy-satellite-network-us-intelligence-agency-sources-2024-03-16)
  - Elon Musk's SpaceX is developing a network of advanced spy satellites under a secretive contract with a U.S. intelligence agency.
  - The project involves SpaceX's Starshield business unit and has been valued at around $1.8 billion.
  - This collaboration highlights growing connections between SpaceX and national security organizations.  - If successful, the sources said the program would significantly advance the ability of the U.S. government and military to quickly spot potential targets almost anywhere on the globe.
- Roman Sterlingov Found Guilty on Four Counts, Court Finds Chainalysis 'Reliable' [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-03-12/crypto-mixer-convicted-of-money-laundering-on-bitcoin-fog)
  - Roman Sterlingov found guilty on four counts related to money laundering and failure to register a money transmitting service.
  - Defense claims lack of evidence connecting Sterlingov to Bitcoin Fog operations and questions the reliability of Chainalysis.
  - Government argues that Sterlingov operated Bitcoin Fog and used a secretive process despite having an identifiable account linked to him.
  - Appeal expected by the defense due to concerns over the case's evidence and reliance on Chainalysis.- Apple Chip Flaw Lets Hackers Steal Encryption Keys
 - Apple Chip Flaw Lets Hackers Steal Encryption Keys [Zero Day](https://www.zetter-zeroday.com/apple-chips/)
  - A serious security vulnerability affecting Apple's M-series chips allows attackers to steal secret keys from Mac and iPad devices.
  - The issue occurs when systems perform cryptographic functions and affects M1, M2, and M3 chips used since late 2020.
  - Attackers could exploit the vulnerability to steal cryptographic keys stored on devices or secure email communication and cloud accounts.
  - Users cannot address the issue themselves, and the fix lies with cryptographic application developers implementing mitigations and issuing updates to their applications.

